- displacement
environmental_stressor: Accelerating Arctic sea ice loss making traditional ice-edge
  hunting impossible
family_situation: Lives with wife Siku and grandson Malik (8) after his daughter died
  in Nuuk seeking work. His son moved to Denmark. Three generations of hunting knowledge
  concentrated in a man who can no longer hunt.
file_name: a35504f8-8c2f-40e7-b66b-aa07de385da2_g_last_human.json
final_thought: The ice remembers everything - every seal breath, every footstep, every
  prayer. But we are forgetting how to listen.
last_days_scenario: 'Aput sits by his kitchen window at 3 AM, watching the dark ocean
  where solid ice should stretch to the horizon. The weather app shows another warm
  front approaching - 4Â°C above normal for January. His grandson asks why the polar
  bears in his picture book look so fat when the ones on YouTube look so thin. Aput
  has no words in English or Inuktitut for this betrayal by the world itself. Tomorrow
  he will check the ice charts again, knowing what he will find: open water where
  his ancestors walked on solid ground. His wife quietly packs dried fish for another
  winter of rationing, while outside, the wind carries the sound of waves that should
  be frozen silent.'
